It integrates with your build process. Once configured, it\ndetects all your static resources (HTML, JavaScript, CSS, images, etc.) and\ngenerates a hash of each file's contents. Information about each file's URL and\nversioned hash are stored in the generated service worker file, along with logic\nto serve those files cache-first, and automatically keep those files up to date\nwhen changes are detected in subsequent builds.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eServing your local static resources cache-first means that you can get all the\ncrucial scaffolding for your web app—your App Shell—on the screen without having\nto wait for any network responses.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThe module can be used in JavaScript-based build scripts,\nlike those written with \u003ca href=\"http://gulpjs.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003egulp\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, and it also provides a\n\u003ca href=\"#command-line-interface\"\u003ecommand-line interface\u003c/a\u003e. You can use the module\ndirectly, or if you'd prefer, use one of the \u003ca href=\"#wrappers-and-starter-kits\"\u003ewrappers\u003c/a\u003e\naround \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e for dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMake sure your site is served using HTTPS!\u003c/strong\u003e\nService worker functionality is only available on pages that are accessed via HTTPS.\n(\u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost\u003c/code\u003e will also work, to facilitate testing.) The rationale for this restriction is\noutlined in the\n\u003ca href=\"http://www.chromium.org/Home/chromium-security/prefer-secure-origins-for-powerful-new-features\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003e\"Prefer Secure Origins For Powerful New Features\" document\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIncorporate \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e into your \u003ccode\u003enode\u003c/code\u003e-based build script.\u003c/strong\u003e It should\nwork well with either \u003ccode\u003egulp\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eGrunt\u003c/code\u003e, or other build scripts that run on\n\u003ccode\u003enode\u003c/code\u003e. In fact, we've provided examples of both in the \u003ccode\u003edemo/\u003c/code\u003e directory. Each\nbuild script in \u003ccode\u003edemo\u003c/code\u003e has a function called \u003ccode\u003ewriteServiceWorkerFile()\u003c/code\u003e that\nshows how to use the API. Both scripts generate fully-functional JavaScript code\nthat takes care of precaching and fetching all the resources your site needs to\nfunction offline. There is also a \u003ca href=\"#command-line-interface\"\u003ecommand-line interface\u003c/a\u003e\navailable, for those using alternate build setups.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRegister the service worker JavaScript.\u003c/strong\u003e The JavaScript that's generated\nneeds to be registered as the controlling service worker for your pages. This\ntechnically only needs to be done from within a top-level \"entry\" page for your\nsite, since the registration includes a \u003ca href=\"https://slightlyoff.github.io/ServiceWorker/spec/service_worker/index.html#service-worker-registration-scope\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003escope\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\nwhich will apply to all pages underneath your top-level page. \u003ca href=\"/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/demo/app/js/service-worker-registration.js\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003eservice-worker-registration.js\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is a sample\nscript that illustrates the best practices for registering the generated service\nworker and handling the various \u003ca href=\"https://slightlyoff.github.io/ServiceWorker/spec/service_worker/index.html#service-worker-state.1\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003elifecycle\u003c/a\u003e dir=\"auto\"\u003eService worker caching should be considered a progressive enhancement. If you follow the model of\nconditionally registering a service worker only if it's supported (determined by\n\u003ccode\u003eif('serviceWorker' in navigator)\u003c/code\u003e), you'll get offline support on browsers with service workers and\non browsers that don't support service workers, the offline-specific code will never be called.\nThere's no overhead/breakage for older browsers if you add \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e to your build.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAll\u003c/strong\u003e resources that are precached will be fetched by a service worker running in a separate\nthread as soon as the service worker is installed. You should be judicious in what you list in the\n\u003ccode\u003edynamicUrlToDependencies\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003estaticFileGlobs\u003c/code\u003e options, since listing files that are non-essential\n(large images that are not shown on every page, for instance) will result in browsers downloading\nmore data than is strictly necessary.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003ePrecaching doesn't make sense for all types of resources (see the previous\npoint). Other caching strategies, like those outlined in the \u003ca href=\"https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/instant-and-offline/offline-cookbook/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003eOffline Cookbook\u003c/a\u003e, can be used in\nconjunction with \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e to provide the best experience for your users. If\nyou do implement additional caching logic, put the code in a separate JavaScript\nfile and include it using the \u003ccode\u003eimportScripts()\u003c/code\u003e method.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e uses a \u003ca href=\"http://jakearchibald.com/2014/offline-cookbook/#cache-falling-back-to-network\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ecache-first\u003c/a\u003e strategy, which results in a copy of\nany cached content being returned without consulting the network. A useful\npattern to adopt with this strategy is to display a toast/alert to your users\nwhen there's new content available, and give them an opportunity to reload the\npage to pick up that new content (which the service worker will have added to\nthe cache, and will be available at the next page load). The sample \u003ca href=\"/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/demo/app/js/service-worker-registration.js\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003eservice-worker-registration.js\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/a\u003e file \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/GoogleChrome/sw-precache/blob/7688ee8ccdaddd9171af352384d04d16d712f9d3/demo/app/js/service-worker-registration.js#L51\"\u003eillustrates\u003c/a\u003e\nthe service worker lifecycle event you can listen for to trigger this message.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"markdown-heading\" dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ch3 tabindex=\"-1\" \u003ccode\u003e--no\u003c/code\u003e prefix negate the boolean value. For example, \u003ccode\u003e--no-clients-claim\u003c/code\u003e sets the value of \u003ccode\u003eclientsClaim\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWarning:\u003c/strong\u003e When using \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e \"by hand\", outside of an automated build process, it's your\nresponsibility to re-run the command each time there's a change to any local resources! If \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e\nis not run again, the previously cached local resources will be reused indefinitely.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eSensible defaults are assumed for options that are not provided. Requests\nthat are fulfilled with out-of-date responses (like those found in your\nbrowser's HTTP cache) can end up being read from the service worker's cache\nindefinitely. Jake Archibald's \u003ca href=\"https://jakearchibald.com/2016/caching-best-practices/#a-service-worker-can-extend-the-life-of-these-bugs\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003eblog post\u003c/a\u003e\nprovides more context about this problem.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eIn the interest of avoiding that scenario, \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e will, by default,\nappend a cache-busting parameter to the end of each URL it requests when\npopulating or updating its cache. Developers who are explicitly doing \"the right\nthing\" when it comes to setting HTTP caching headers on their responses might\nwant to opt out of this cache-busting. For example, if all of your static\nresources already include versioning information in their URLs (via a tool like\n\u003ca href=\"https://github.com/sindresorhus/gulp-rev\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003egulp-rev\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/a\u003e), and are served with\nlong-lived HTTP caching headers, then the extra cache-busting URL parameter\nis not needed, and can be safely excluded.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003edontCacheBustUrlsMatching\u003c/code\u003e gives you a way of opting-in to skipping the cache\nbusting behavior for a subset of your URLs (or all of them, if a catch-all value\nlike \u003ccode\u003e/./\u003c/code\u003e is used).\nIf set, then the \u003ca href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTMLHyperlinkElementUtils/pathname\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003epathname\u003c/a\u003e\nof each URL that's prefetched will be matched against this value.\nIf there's a match, then the URL will be prefetched as-is, without an additional\ncache-busting URL parameter appended.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eNote: Prior to \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e v5.0.0, \u003ccode\u003edontCacheBustUrlsMatching\u003c/code\u003e matched against\nthe entire request URL. 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Service Worker Precache is a module for generating a service worker thatprecaches resources. It integrates with your build process. Once configured, itdetects all your static resources (HTML, JavaScript, CSS, images, etc.) andgenerates a hash of each file's contents. Information about each file's URL andversioned hash are stored in the generated service worker file, along with logicto serve those files cache-first, and automatically keep those files up to datewhen changes are detected in subsequent builds.</p><p dir="auto">Serving your local static resources cache-first means that you can get all thecrucial scaffolding for your web app—your App Shell—on the screen without havingto wait for any network responses.</p><p dir="auto">The module can be used in JavaScript-based build scripts,like those written with <a href="http://gulpjs.com/" rel="nofollow"><code>gulp</code></a>, and it also provides a<a href="#command-line-interface">command-line interface</a>. You can use the moduledirectly, or if you'd prefer, use one of the <a href="#wrappers-and-starter-kits">wrappers</a>around <code>sw-precache</code> for specific build environments, like<a href="https://webpack.github.io/" rel="nofollow"><code>webpack</code></a>.</p><p dir="auto">It can be <a href="/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/sw-precache-and-sw-toolbox.md">used alongside</a> the <a href="https://github.com/GoogleChrome/sw-toolbox"><code>sw-toolbox</code></a>library, which works well when following the App Shell + dynamic content model.</p><p dir="auto">The full documentation is in this README, and the<a href="/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/GettingStarted.md">getting started guide</a> provides a quicker jumping off point.</p><p dir="auto">To learn more about the internals of the generated service worker, you can read<a href="https://medium.com/@Huxpro/how-does-sw-precache-works-2d99c3d3c725" rel="nofollow">this deep-dive</a>by <a href="https://twitter.com/Huxpro" rel="nofollow">Huang Xuan</a>.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h1 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Table of Contents</h1><a HTTPS.(<code>http://localhost</code> will also work, to facilitate testing.) The rationale for this restriction isoutlined in the<a href="http://www.chromium.org/Home/chromium-security/prefer-secure-origins-for-powerful-new-features" rel="nofollow">"Prefer Secure Origins For Powerful New Features" document</a>.</p></li><li><p dir="auto"><strong>Incorporate <code>sw-precache</code> into your <code>node</code>-based build script.</strong> It shouldwork well with either <code>gulp</code> or <code>Grunt</code>, or other build scripts that run on<code>node</code>. In fact, we've provided examples of both in the <code>demo/</code> directory. Eachbuild script in <code>demo</code> has a function called <code>writeServiceWorkerFile()</code> thatshows how to use the API. Both scripts generate fully-functional JavaScript codethat takes care of precaching and fetching all the resources your site needs tofunction offline. There is also a <a href="#command-line-interface">command-line interface</a>available, for those using alternate build setups.</p></li><li><p dir="auto"><strong>Register the service worker JavaScript.</strong> The JavaScript that's generatedneeds to be registered as the controlling service worker for your pages. Thistechnically only needs to be done from within a top-level "entry" page for yoursite, since the registration includes a <a href="https://slightlyoff.github.io/ServiceWorker/spec/service_worker/index.html#service-worker-registration-scope" rel="nofollow"><code>scope</code></a>which will apply to all pages underneath your top-level page. <a href="/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/demo/app/js/service-worker-registration.js"><code>service-worker-registration.js</code></a> is a samplescript that illustrates the best practices for registering the generated serviceworker and handling the various <a href="https://slightlyoff.github.io/ServiceWorker/spec/service_worker/index.html#service-worker-state.1" rel="nofollow">lifecycle</a> events.</p></li></ol><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Example</h3><a id="user-content-example" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Example" href="#example"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">The project's <a href="/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/demo/gulpfile.js">sample <code>gulpfile.js</code></a> illustrates the full use of sw-precachein context. class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Considerations</h3><a id="user-content-considerations" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Considerations" href="#considerations"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 progressive enhancement. If you follow the model ofconditionally registering a service worker only if it's supported (determined by<code>if('serviceWorker' in navigator)</code>), you'll get offline support on browsers with service workers andon browsers that don't support service workers, the offline-specific code will never be called.There's no overhead/breakage for older browsers if you add <code>sw-precache</code> to your build.</p></li><li><p dir="auto"><strong>All</strong> resources that are precached will be fetched by a service worker running in a separatethread as soon as the service worker is installed. You should be judicious in what you list in the<code>dynamicUrlToDependencies</code> and <code>staticFileGlobs</code> options, since listing files that are non-essential(large images that are not shown on every page, for instance) will result in browsers downloadingmore data than is strictly necessary.</p></li><li><p dir="auto">Precaching doesn't make sense for all types of resources (see the previouspoint). Other caching strategies, like those outlined in the <a href="https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/instant-and-offline/offline-cookbook/" rel="nofollow">Offline Cookbook</a>, can be used inconjunction with <code>sw-precache</code> to provide the best experience for your users. Ifyou do implement additional caching logic, put the code in a separate JavaScriptfile and include it using the <code>importScripts()</code> method.</p></li><li><p dir="auto"><code>sw-precache</code> uses a <a href="http://jakearchibald.com/2014/offline-cookbook/#cache-falling-back-to-network" rel="nofollow">cache-first</a> strategy, which results in a copy ofany cached content being returned without consulting the network. A usefulpattern to adopt with this strategy is to display a toast/alert to your userswhen there's new content available, and give them an opportunity to reload thepage to pick up that new content (which the service worker will have added tothe cache, and will be available at the next page load). The sample <a href="/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/demo/app/js/service-worker-registration.js"><code>service-worker-registration.js</code></a> file <a href="https://github.com/GoogleChrome/sw-precache/blob/7688ee8ccdaddd9171af352384d04d16d712f9d3/demo/app/js/service-worker-registration.js#L51">illustrates</a>the service worker lifecycle event you can listen for to trigger this message.</p></li></ul><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Command-line interface</h3><a id="user-content-command-line-interface" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Command-line interface" href="#command-line-interface"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">For those who would prefer not to use <code>sw-precache</code> as part of a <code>gulp</code> or<code>Grunt</code> build, there's a <a href="/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache/blob/master/cli.js">command-line interface</a> which supports the<a href="#options-parameter">options listed</a> in the API, provided via flags or anexternal JavaScript configuration file.</p><p dir="auto">Hypenated flags are converted to camelCase <a href="#options-parameter">options</a>.<br>Options starting with <code>--no</code> prefix negate the boolean value. For example, <code>--no-clients-claim</code> sets the value of <code>clientsClaim</code> to <code>false</code>.</p><p dir="auto"><strong>Warning:</strong> When using <code>sw-precache</code> "by hand", outside of an automated build process, it's yourresponsibility to re-run the command each time there's a change to any local resources! If <code>sw-precache</code>is not run again, the previously cached local resources will be reused indefinitely.</p><p dir="auto">Sensible defaults are assumed for options that are not provided. For example, if you are insidethe top-level directory that contains your site's contents, and you'd like to generate a<code>service-worker.js</code> file that will automatically precache all of the local files, you can simply run</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ sw-precache"><pre>$ sw-precache</pre></div><p dir="auto">Alternatively, if you'd like to only precache <code>.html</code> files that live within <code>dist/</code>, which is asubdirectory of the current directory, you could run</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ sw-precache --root=dist --static-file-globs='dist/**/*.html'"><pre>$ sw-precache --root=dist --static-file-globs=<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">'</span>dist/**/*.html<span class="pl-pds">'</span></span></pre></div><p dir="auto"><strong>Note:</strong> Be sure to use quotes around parameter values that have special meaningsto your shell (such as the <code>*</code> characters in the sample command line above,for example).</p><p dir="auto">Finally, there's support for passing complex configurations using <code>--config <file></code>.Any of the options from the file can be overridden via a command-line flag.We strongly recommend passing it an external JavaScript file defining config via<a href="https://nodejs.org/api/modules.html#modules_module_exports" rel="nofollow"><code>module.exports</code></a>.For example, assume there's a <code>path/to/sw-precache-config.js</code> file that contains:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-js notranslate You may have seen our <a href="https://github.com/GoogleChrome/sw-toolbox"><code>sw-toolbox</code></a> tool, which handles runtime caching, and wondered how to use them together. Fortunately, <code>sw-precache</code> handles this for you.</p><p dir="auto">The <code>sw-precache</code> module has the ability to include the <code>sw-toolbox</code> code and configuration alongside its own configuration.
